  <!-- 01 Brief -->
  <article class="chapter">
    <div class="chapter-num mono">
      <span>CHAPTER</span>
      <span class="big">01</span>
    </div>
    <div>
      <div class="kicker mono">THE BRIEF</div>
      <h2>Most companies have no idea what their attack surface looks like.</h2>
      <p class="lede">A small team owns five domains, twelve subdomains, and an old marketing landing page nobody has touched in three years. The marketing page still has SSH open. They will not find this until somebody else does.</p>
      <div class="body">
        <p>Commercial attack-surface tools solve this — at five figures a year and a procurement cycle the kind of company that needs them most cannot run. The free tools solve fragments of it: a port scanner here, a subdomain enumerator there, a header checker as a browser extension. None of them produce a single artifact you can hand to an engineer on a Monday morning.</p>
        <p>I built Scanner because I kept stitching those fragments together by hand on every personal pentest engagement and got tired of it. The goal was modest: one binary, one command, one readable report that fits on the screen.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </article>

  <!-- 02 Approach -->
  <article class="chapter">
    <div class="chapter-num mono">
      <span>CHAPTER</span>
      <span class="big">02</span>
    </div>
    <div>
      <div class="kicker mono">THE APPROACH</div>
      <h2>One binary. Concurrent everything. Two outputs.</h2>
      <div class="body">
        <p>The hard part of recon is not any individual probe — it is doing all of them in parallel without melting the network or the target. Scanner runs each module as an async task with bounded concurrency, shared rate limits, and a single result bus that the report writer drains.</p>
        <p>Every check writes two outputs: a coloured terminal block for the engineer running it live, and a structured JSON entry for whatever pipeline picks it up downstream. The same run can drive a CI failure, a Slack alert, or just a human reading the screen.</p>
        <p>The modules are deliberately small. DNS resolution. Subdomain enumeration via certificate transparency logs. Port scan with banner grab. TLS configuration. Security header audit. Six modules that, together, cover most of the surface a stranger could see from the internet without touching anything sensitive.</p>
      </div>

