  <!-- 03 Findings -->
  <article class="chapter">
    <div class="chapter-num mono">
      <span>CHAPTER</span>
      <span class="big">03</span>
    </div>
    <div>
      <div class="kicker mono">THE FINDINGS</div>
      <h2>What it keeps catching.</h2>
      <p class="lede">Run on a few dozen domains across personal engagements and friends-of-friends startups, the same patterns kept landing on the report. None of them are exotic. All of them are exploitable.</p>

      <div class="findings">
        <div class="finding">
          <div class="idx mono">F.01 · STALE DEV SUBDOMAINS</div>
          <h3>Forgotten staging boxes pointing at production data.</h3>
          <p>A <code>staging.acme.com</code> from a launch two years ago, still resolving, still serving an old Rails admin panel with a default credential set.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="finding">
          <div class="idx mono">F.02 · MISSING SECURITY HEADERS</div>
          <h3>HSTS, CSP, and frame-options absent on the marketing site.</h3>
          <p>Easy to fix, almost universally missing. The marketing page is the one most likely to be cloned for phishing — and the one nobody on the security team owns.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="finding">
          <div class="idx mono">F.03 · DEPRECATED TLS</div>
          <h3>TLS 1.0/1.1 still enabled on internal-looking endpoints.</h3>
          <p>Usually a load balancer somebody set up before the rest of the stack moved. Modern clients refuse the connection; older bots cheerfully downgrade.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="finding">
          <div class="idx mono">F.04 · EXPOSED ADMIN PORTS</div>
          <h3>SSH, Postgres, Redis on public IPs without an IP allowlist.</h3>
          <p>Bound to <code>0.0.0.0</code> behind a security group nobody re-audited after the last cloud migration. The port scan finds them in seconds.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="finding">
          <div class="idx mono">F.05 · DNS MISCONFIGURATION</div>
          <h3>SPF, DKIM, and DMARC missing or set to <code>p=none</code>.</h3>
          <p>The mailbox is configured. The records are not. Domain spoofing is one DNS query away from being trivial.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="finding">
          <div class="idx mono">F.06 · LEAKED INTERNAL HOSTS</div>
          <h3>Certificate transparency reveals internal naming.</h3>
          <p>Internal subdomains the team never expected to be public — <code>vault.</code>, <code>hr.</code>, <code>build.</code> — listed in CT logs. The hostnames alone tell an attacker where to push.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </article>

  <!-- 04 Harness -->
  <article class="chapter">
    <div class="chapter-num mono">
      <span>CHAPTER</span>
      <span class="big">04</span>
    </div>
    <div>
      <div class="kicker mono">THE HARNESS</div>
      <h2>One command, two surfaces.</h2>
      <div class="body">
        <p>The interface is intentionally narrow. A target, optional flags for which modules to run, and a destination for the report. Nothing else needs configuration — the defaults are tuned for the case where the engineer just wants the answer.</p>
        <p>The JSON output is stable: each finding has an id, a severity, a module, a target, and a payload. CI integrations diff yesterday's run against today's and only fail when something new appears. The terminal output is what people show in a screenshot when they file the ticket.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="code-head mono">scanner · terminal session</div>
      <pre class="code"><span class="c"># sweep a domain, write JSON, surface findings to the terminal</span>
$ scanner scan acme.com --modules all --out report.json

<span class="k">→</span> dns         <span class="f">resolved 4 records · 11ms</span>
<span class="k">→</span> subdomains  <span class="f">found 23 via CT · 412ms</span>
<span class="k">→</span> ports       <span class="f">scanned 1024 · 3 open · 6.1s</span>
<span class="k">→</span> tls         <span class="f">tls 1.0 enabled on api.acme.com · weak</span>
<span class="k">→</span> headers     <span class="f">missing HSTS, CSP, X-Frame-Options</span>
<span class="k">→</span> fingerprint <span class="f">nginx 1.18 · openssh 7.4</span>

<span class="s">findings: 6 (1 high · 3 medium · 2 low)   total: 28.4s</span></pre>

      <div class="body" style="margin-top: 32px;">
        <p>The continuous mode is a thin wrapper around the same binary: a cron entry, a JSON diff, a webhook. Nothing about the engine had to change to make it work — which was the point of the design.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </article>

  <!-- 05 Outcome -->
  <article class="chapter">
    <div class="chapter-num mono">
      <span>CHAPTER</span>
      <span class="big">05</span>
    </div>
    <div>
      <div class="kicker mono">THE OUTCOME</div>
      <h2>Boring tool, real findings.</h2>
      <div class="body">
        <p>Scanner is open source and intentionally unflashy. There is no dashboard, no SaaS, no login. It is a single binary that does one thing well and stays out of the way of the engineer running it. A handful of teams use it as the first step of their pentest engagements; a smaller handful run it on a nightly cron against their own surface.</p>
        <p>The interesting outcome is not the tool itself — it is what showed up in the reports. The finding pattern above repeated almost verbatim across every engagement. Not exotic vulnerabilities. Forgotten infrastructure. Configurations that nobody owned. Things that one nightly run would have caught months earlier.</p>
        <p>That is the case for a tool like this existing in the open: most companies do not have an attack-surface problem because they cannot fix the issues. They have one because nobody is looking. Scanner makes looking the cheap part.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </article>

